00:45:30.491 --> 00:45:36.650
U.S. News World report rankings. Hospitals care a lot about those. So that got leadership attention.

00:45:36.650 --> 00:45:41.371
So that's, that was one where like, oh, you know what, we can't really do these in

00:45:41.371 --> 00:45:45.770
ClickSense or in like, I think we had SAS Visual Analytics at the time. So

00:45:48.491 --> 00:45:51.770
yeah, sometimes you have to make the case for it and put the extra time in, but.

00:45:52.491 --> 00:46:03.531
Awesome. Well, I have a question here from Ruby. Ruby, if you are able to ask your question live,

00:46:03.531 --> 00:46:09.130
I will highlight it in Slido. There's Ruby. Hey, Ruby.

00:46:11.531 --> 00:46:16.650
Hey, I'm actually also at Emory. I'm a postdoc in the Department of Epidemiology.

00:46:17.611 --> 00:46:22.250
And so I'm curious, because we don't have that many public health adjacent speakers here,

00:46:23.291 --> 00:46:27.931
whether you can speak to the experience of kind of transitioning into a more data science role

00:46:27.931 --> 00:46:33.210
from public health, either from your experience or that of your people on your team, and what's

00:46:33.210 --> 00:46:37.770
made that kind of easier or what are some of the hurdles that you've encountered? Thanks.

00:46:39.690 --> 00:46:46.171
Yeah, that's a great question. I mean, yeah, so many angles to start from, but I think from like

00:46:46.810 --> 00:46:50.731
kind of like the quantitative skills, like number one, like if you're in epidemiology,

00:46:51.291 --> 00:46:58.411
there's a lot of kind of rigor around working with data and with numbers that directly can

00:46:58.411 --> 00:47:04.971
be leveraged in a data science career. Particularly when I started, or sorry, when I moved to,

00:47:06.171 --> 00:47:10.250
you know, more from research to data science, there really weren't that many programs that

00:47:10.250 --> 00:47:15.450
would formally train you in, like, and people were getting an MIS degree or like Master's

00:47:15.450 --> 00:47:19.851
in Information Science and so on. But there was quite a bit of openness to coming from different

00:47:19.851 --> 00:47:30.091
fields. And I think for public health, the thinking around like, you know, scientific

00:47:30.091 --> 00:47:38.010
thinking and also biostats and epi kind of quantitative rigor lends itself well to the

00:47:38.010 --> 00:47:43.611
biggest, I think that's one of the steepest parts of the curve is like learning these tools,

00:47:43.611 --> 00:47:50.010
or sorry, learning the methods. As far as like programming, kind of the other big part of data

00:47:50.010 --> 00:47:56.171
science is like, can you turn your analyses into something actionable and something that

00:47:56.971 --> 00:48:06.810
is repeatable? Again, I think compared to a decade ago, like using tools like Quarta or Markdown

00:48:06.810 --> 00:48:12.570
is kind of a basic starting point. And they're great for research, but they also have kind of the

00:48:12.650 --> 00:48:18.330
basic premise of making sure your code is reproducible. So just scripting to do statistical

00:48:18.330 --> 00:48:24.330
analysis is one thing, making something truly repeatable, both like for replicating your

00:48:24.330 --> 00:48:30.171
findings, but also to translate to your other projects is a big part of data science, right?

00:48:32.330 --> 00:48:41.371
And then as far as like actually transitioning in terms of culture shift, I think healthcare

00:48:41.371 --> 00:48:47.770
was a great place for me at that point, because there is a lot of understanding about, you know,

00:48:48.491 --> 00:48:55.450
you're still working with people that are been through the biosciences. So I find it easier to

00:48:55.450 --> 00:49:01.931
talk to people that are clinical and if you're coming from public health, because

00:49:03.371 --> 00:49:09.210
they have a lot of understanding, respect and similar foundation knowledge.

00:49:10.010 --> 00:49:17.770
And then, you know, if you go further, I think the trade off is like, if you go more into

00:49:17.770 --> 00:49:22.171
technology, for example, once I moved out of healthcare, I went into more like,

00:49:23.051 --> 00:49:28.491
like more the insurance side of things, or it was more payer, you get kind of a deeper

00:49:28.491 --> 00:49:36.171
understanding of technology there, because they have different data challenges. So I think that

00:49:36.250 --> 00:49:41.051
was important, but you lose some of that connection with people around,

00:49:43.051 --> 00:49:47.130
you know, the way of thinking, the kind of shared mental models around,

00:49:48.731 --> 00:49:51.051
you know, hypothesis testing, for example, or

00:49:53.851 --> 00:49:58.491
just the mission and values appreciation as well. But you learn a lot of other things.

00:50:01.531 --> 00:50:02.491
Always a trade off.

00:50:03.291 --> 00:50:09.130
Mm hmm. Yeah. And the other part I would say, LLMs have made it much easier with coding also

00:50:09.130 --> 00:50:14.890
to create production grade code, or maybe not quite production grade code, but to cross that

00:50:14.890 --> 00:50:20.890
barrier into, I don't know how to program. So maybe that looks very different now than

00:50:22.171 --> 00:50:26.810
for someone making that call like 10 years ago to go into data science.

00:50:26.810 --> 00:50:32.171
It's a different world now. Ruby, that was such a great question. Thank you for asking that.

